</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/umaldisdainatheist.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Maldisdain Atheist</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Elementalist</span><br>  Posts: 92<br> <font color=#333333>(6/11/02 5:10:26 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm32.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=237.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://dynamic.gamespy.com/~cazic/cazic/ubb/uploads/StaffOfSerpent2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Fixing Burnout by Raising Pet Haste Cap</span><hr size=1> On Attack--<br>
<br>
The general consensus I've seen on the effects of Attack is that +100 attack yields +~15% damage, by shifting the distribution of damage curve towards higher damage.<br>
<br>
Thus, for example, if a mage pet hit like this without an attack increase:<br>
<!--EZCODE CODE START--><pre> 
Damage:   07   17   27   37   47   57   67   77
# of hits: 1    3    5    7    7    5    3    1
</pre><!--EZCODE CODE END--><br>
<br>
it might hit like this with a substantial attack bonus:<br>
<!--EZCODE CODE START--><pre> 
Damage:   07   17   27   37   47   57   67   77
# of hits: 0    1    3    5    7    7    5    4
</pre><!--EZCODE CODE END--><br>
<br>
Attack is <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> the major factor</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> in determining the distribution of damage over a period of time.<br>
-----<br>
<br>
Personally, I am a firm believer in attack.  Though I have my Staff of the Serpent, I use Visions of Grandeur (for it's attack &amp; dex increases) almost exclusively in both groups and raids.  My pets receive VoG exclusively, and even the small +20 attack makes a fairly substantial difference in damage output (albeit one that I've judged entirely subjectively).<br>
-----<br>
<br>
Were I a mage, and I am not, I would request that the Burnout series be changed to have a substantial attack increase component (perhaps 30x burnout rating) and a relatively minimal haste component.  While this would decrease the pet's strength at soloing, it would substantially increase the damage output of pets in raid scenarios, where they would be able to benefit from 3rd party haste spells.  <br>
<br>
With a +18% damage increase from [a ~120 attack increase from a retuned Burnout 4], extrapolated from Cyricus Bloodbane's data, the Epic Pet would come in at 22.4 DPS (24.4 with Muzzle).  In solo situations, this is a reduction of ~8 DPS (~25%) on a self-buffed pet.  <br>
<br>
In group/raid situations, however, the epic pet would come in around 37.8 DPS, an increase of ~6 DPS (18%).<br>
-----<br>
<br>
The advantages of this change, in my opinion, are:<br>
(1) an increase in Mage DPS in the situations where they need them most--raid scenarios.<br>
(2) an increase in class interdependency which, in my opinion, is an essential part of EverQuest.<br>
<br>
Muzzle of Mardu would be more valuable were it the primary source of master-controlled pet haste, but I think this is at best an artificial &quot;advantage&quot; of this change.<br>
<br>
The primary disadvantage is:<br>
(1) decreased pet DPS in true solo situations.<br>
-----<br>
<br>
It's <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> a</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> solution, anyway... I'll try to dig up the link to the Avatar/attack discussion over on the Ranger boards from which I derive the 15% number after work.<br>
